{"title_page": "Stats Perform", "text_new": "{{short description|US sports technology and data company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Stats Perform\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| logo                = \n| logo_size           = \n| logo_alt            = \n| logo_caption        = \n| logo_padding        = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = \n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| founded             = {{start date|1981|04|30}}\n| founder             = John Dewan\n| hq_location         = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| hq_location_city    = \n| hq_location_country = \n| area_served         = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people          = Carl Mergele (CEO)\n| industry            = Sports Technology and Data\n| products            = Sports data, analytics and team tracking solutions\n| brands              = Omnisports, [[Opta Sports]], [[Prozone Sports Ltd|Prozone]], [[TVTI]], [[Automated Insights]], [[The Sports Network (wire service)|The Sports Network]], [[BSports]]\n| services            = \n| owner               = Vista Equity Partners\n| website             = {{URL|statsperform.com}}\n| former_name         = \n}}\n\n'''Stats Perform''' (formerly '''STATS LLC''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=739452|title=STATS LLC: Private Company Information|website=[[Bloomberg.com]]|access-date=2018-09-23}}</ref> is a [[Chicago]]-based sports data and [[sports analytics|analytics]] company.\n\nThe company is involved in sports data collection and [[Predictive analytics|predictive analysis]], and maintains sports-oriented [[wire service]]s. The company has also been increasingly involved in [[artificial intelligence]] and [[machine learning]].<ref name=\"sporttechie.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sporttechie.com/the-evolution-of-stats-llc-and-its-place-in-the-sports-technology-landscape/|title=The Evolution of STATS LLC And Its Place In The Sports Technology Landscape|website=SportTechie|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> Its clients include media outlets, sports leagues and teams, [[fantasy sports]] and [[sports betting]] services. As of 2014, the company covered 83,000 events annually from over 300 leagues and competitions. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = With clients like the NBA and Google, STATS is the coolest data company you've never heard of|url = http://www.builtinchicago.org/2014/02/25/clients-nba-and-google-stats-coolest-data-company-youve-never-heard|website = Built In Chicago|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref> In 2019, it merged with [[Perform Group|Perform Content]] following its sale to parent company Vista Equity Partners.\n\nStats Perform is headquartered in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], with other corporate offices in [[Limerick]], [[London]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Tokyo]], [[Beijing]], [[Bangalore]], [[Dubai]], [[The Hague]], [[Mexico City]], [[Barcelona]], [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]].\n\n==History==\nSTATS was founded in April 1981<ref name=\"timeline\">[http://biz.stats.com/timeline.asp STATS website: Timeline]</ref> by John Dewan,<ref>[http://www.actasports.com/detail.html?id=9780879463670 ACTA Sports: The Bill James Handbook 2009]</ref> who became the company's CEO. The company name is an acronym for \"Sports Team Analysis and Tracking Systems\". STATS was an outgrowth of the grassroots non-profit Project Scoresheet, a volunteer network created to collect [[sabermetrics|baseball statistics.]]<ref>{{Cite book|title = Keep Score, Project Scoresheet\u2013Style|url = https://www.safaribooksonline.com/library/view/baseball-hacks/0596009429/ch01s04.html|first = Safari Books|last = Online}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996 STATS and [[Motorola]] won on appeal a court case brought by the NBA. The case was barring STATS from distributing in-game information via a special wireless device created by Motorola.  The victory in this case has played a large part in other cases where professional sports leagues have tried to suppress live in-game information being distributed by other outlets.<ref>[http://legal.web.aol.com/decisions/dldecen/nba.html NBA Lawsuit - AOL.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702231859/http://legal.web.aol.com/decisions/dldecen/nba.html |date=July 2, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, STATS expanded to the [[National Football League]], the [[National Basketball Association]], the [[National Hockey League]], the [[Women's National Basketball Association]], in addition to other sports.<ref name=timeline />\n\n== Acquisitions ==\nSTATS operated as a private company from 1981 to 2000. STATS was purchased by [[Fox Sports (USA)|Fox Sports]] in 2000 and became a joint venture between [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] and the [[Associated Press]] in 2005.\n\nIn 2009, the company acquired the PA SportsTicker wire service from [[Press Association]], a UK news and information company. SportsTicker had previously been owned by [[ESPN]].<ref>http://www.crunchbase.com/company/pa-sportsticker</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, Fox Sports and the AP sold STATS to [[Vista Equity Partners]], a private equity firm.<ref>{{Cite web| last = Ecker| first = Danny| title = Stats LLC sold to private-equity firm| work = Crain's Chicago Business| accessdate = 2015-04-26| date = 2014-05-15| url = http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20140515/BLOGS04/140519841/stats-llc-sold-to-private-equity-firm}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = FOX Sports and AP announce sale of sports data company STATS LLC|url = http://www.ap.org/Content/Press-Release/2014/FOX-Sports-and-The-Associated-Press-Announce-Sale-of-Sports-Data-Company-STATS-LLC|website = www.ap.org|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2014, the platform created over a billion articles and reports for customers such as [[The Associated Press]], [[Yahoo!]], and [[Comcast]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = STATS Gets Into the Robot News Game With Automated Insights Acquisition|url = http://chicagoinno.streetwise.co/2015/02/12/stats-acquires-automated-insights/|website = Chicago Inno|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref> In September 2014, STATS acquired Bloomberg Sports.\n\nIn early 2015, STATS acquired the wire service [[The Sports Network (wire service)|The Sports Network]] and Prozone. Vista Equity Partners also acquired [[Automated Insights]], a company involved in using [[natural-language generation]] based on [[big data]] (including in particular, generating wire reports on sporting events from raw statistics).<ref>{{Cite web|title = Stats LLC Makes Athlete Performance Outfit Prozone Its Latest Acquisition|work= SportsBusiness Daily|publisher=American City Business Journals |url = http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2015/05/05/Finance/Stats.aspx|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Vista Equity Partners announced its intent to acquire Perform Content, the former sports data subsidiary of [[Perform Group]], including units such as Omnisport, [[Opta Sports]], and RunningBall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sbcnews.co.uk/europe/2019/04/03/dazn-nears-entire-data-offload-to-vista-equity/|title=DAZN nears entire data offload to Vista Equity|date=2019-04-03|website=SBC News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref> The company was selling the property to focus more on its sports streaming service [[DAZN]]. It was stated that [[DAZN Group]] would retain a \"significant minority stake\" in the surviving entity, which was to focus strongly on the use of [[artificial intelligence]] and [[machine learning]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/dazn-perform-stats-merge-streaming-business-vista-acquisition|title=DAZN Group to prioritise streaming business as Perform and STATS merge|website=SportsPro |access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/dazn-len-blavatnik-perform-content|title=Report: DAZN owner planning split to increase focus on OTT platform|website=SportsPro|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/broadcasting/dazn-group-sells-perform/5138568.article|title=DAZN Group sells Perform|website=Broadcast|language=en|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> \n\nOn July 15, 2019, it was announced that the merged company would be known as Stats Perform, and operate under STATS CEO Carl Mergele. He stated that the company would \"[harness] the power of immense amounts of sports data with unparalleled AI technology\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/stats-perform-merger-vista-dazn-artificial-intelligence-data|title=STATS and Perform confirm merger|website=SportsPro Media|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Morning-Buzz/2019/07/15/Stats.aspx|title=Stats, Perform Complete Merger, Creating New Data/AI Company|date=15 July 2019|publisher=Sports Business Daily|accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n\nSTATS provides several products to leagues, teams, and the media.\n\nThe X-Info system provides [[National Football League|NFL]], [[college football]] and [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] teams with detailed statistics and information to help them interpret the various metrics.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Football Is Closer to Becoming Moneyball Than You May Think (NWS)|url = http://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/05/nfl-big-data.aspx|website = www.fool.com|accessdate = 2015-06-30|first = Jake|last = Mann}}</ref>\n\nTheir SportVU system uses an array of cameras and image processing software to provide real-time player tracking and ball positioning data, as well as statistical analysis of that data. SportVU is used by FIFA, UEFA and a host of flagship European soccer teams.<ref>{{Cite web|title = GOAL! Wait, was that in? How tech will answer the question at the World Cup|url = http://www.digitaltrends.com/sports/goal-wait-tech-will-answer-question-world-cup/|accessdate = 2015-07-16}}</ref>\n\nNearly every franchise in three of [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|North America's four major professional sports leagues]] (NFL, MLB, and NHL) uses products from STATS.<ref name=\"sporttechie.com\"/>\n\nWith the acquisition of The Sports Network, STATS took over publication of that company's NCAA [[NCAA Division I#Football Championship Subdivision|Division I FCS]] football poll.\n\n==See also==\n[[Elias Sports Bureau]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs = http://stats.nba.com/tracking/#!/player/\nhttp://www.fastcompany.com/most-innovative-companies/2014/stats\nhttp://www.fsta.org/?AwardWinners\nhttp://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/05/nfl-big-data.aspx}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.statsperform.com}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball statistics]]\n[[Category:Former News Corporation subsidiaries]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|US sports technology and data company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Stats Perform\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| founded = {{start date|1981|04|30}}\n| founder = John Dewan\n| hq_location = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = \n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = Carl Mergele (CEO)\n| industry = Sports Technology and Data\n| products = Sports data, analytics and team tracking solutions\n| brands = Omnisports, [[Opta Sports]], [[Prozone Sports Ltd|Prozone]], [[TVTI]], [[Automated Insights]], [[The Sports Network (wire service)|The Sports Network]], [[BSports